### Task Sizing

Each task should be ≈ one commit's worth of work — small enough that the verification step is unambiguous. Write tasks as 2-line entries:

- line 1 — the action as a checkbox bullet, e.g. `- [ ] Add X`
- line 2 — an indented `verify:` line stating the command or observation that proves the task is done

If you can't write the `verify:` line in one sentence, the task is too big. Split it.

A task may also be marked `[deferred]` (e.g., `- [deferred] multiply — moved to M<N+1>`) to signal that the work was intentionally moved out of this milestone. `/ship-milestone` treats `[deferred]` as ship-OK and `/gate-check` skips it from the task-FR coverage probe.

**Anti-patterns — tasks too large to verify cleanly:**

- `- [ ] Implement entire feature` — "entire feature" is a milestone, not a task; you can't verify it in one step
- `- [ ] Refactor and add tests and update docs` — conjunctions hide three separate commits' worth of work; each clause needs its own `verify:` line
- `- [ ] Clean up technical debt` — no observable end state; can't tell when it's done

